---
import Base from '../../../layouts/Base.astro';
import StatBand from '../../../components/StatBand.astro';
---

<Base
  title="SUPES Academy: the national standard for superintendent development — Case Study | Tom Vranas"
  description="Saw that the country had no real path to train its most complex public-sector executives — and built it. The largest superintendent-development company in the United States, demand-pulled into a full leadership pipeline."
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="back-link">
        <a href="/experience?view=case-studies">&larr; Case studies</a>
      </p>
      <p class="eyebrow" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">Case Study &middot; 2010&ndash;2015</p>
      <h1 style="margin-top: 0.9rem;">
        There was no path to the hardest job in public education. So we built one.
      </h1>

      <p style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">
        Running Proact Search, I kept seeing the same thing from inside the executive search: the
        superintendent bench was dangerously thin. Young talent wasn&rsquo;t growing into the role,
        and the reason was simple &mdash; there was no path, no training, no on-ramp for one of the
        most complex executive jobs in the country. A superintendent runs a
        multi-hundred-million-dollar organization, answers to an elected board, and carries the
        futures of tens of thousands of kids. Nobody was preparing them for it. So we set out to
        build the infrastructure that didn&rsquo;t exist.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section--ink" aria-label="At a glance">
    <div class="container">
      <StatBand
        stats={[
          { value: '70%', label: 'Landed a superintendency' },
          { value: '#1', label: 'Largest in the U.S.' },
          { value: '$10M', label: 'Peak annual revenue' },
          { value: '200+', label: 'National consultant network' },
        ]}
      />
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container cs-steps">
      <h2 class="cs-step">Context</h2>
      <p style="margin-top: 0.7rem;">
        The work of becoming a superintendent had no standard training ground. Aspiring leaders were
        expected to learn the job by surviving it. We acquired a proven executive-development
        methodology and built a national academy around it &mdash; an executive-MBA-style program
        designed to teach the genuinely complex sides of the role, not the theory of leadership.
      </p>

      <h2 class="cs-step" style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">Mandate</h2>
      <p style="margin-top: 0.7rem;">
        Take a proven methodology and build it into a national operating company that could actually
        develop the next generation of district leaders &mdash; at scale, with measurable results.
      </p>

      <h2 class="cs-step" style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">Owned</h2>
      <p style="margin-top: 0.7rem;">
        Operations, curriculum development, logistics, data and quality control, and a national
        consultant network of 200+.
      </p>
      <div class="proof-blocks" style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">
        <div class="proof-block">
          <h3>Practitioners, never theorists.</h3>
          <p>
            The defining choice: every member of the faculty was a current, top-tier practitioner
            &mdash; leaders actually doing the job, not academics teaching it from a distance.
            That&rsquo;s what made the program credible to the people in the room, and what made the
            outcomes real.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="proof-block">
          <h3>Demand-pulled into a pipeline.</h3>
          <p>
            We started with one national superintendent academy. Demand surged so fast that one
            became four regional national programs. Then the field told us what to build next:
            graduates landed the job but their central-office teams weren&rsquo;t ready &mdash; so we
            built central-office programs; those leaders said their principals weren&rsquo;t ready
            &mdash; so we built principal programs. Each was a response to a surfaced need, not a
            guess. National cohorts grew 50 to 100 to 200.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="proof-block">
          <h3>National partnerships.</h3>
          <p>
            We partnered with AASA, The School Superintendents Association, to build and run their
            programming for aspiring superintendents &mdash; including specialized programs for
            women, Latino, and urban-district leaders. And we partnered with Apple to create some of
            the first digital textbooks as iPads entered education.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="cs-step" style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">Outcomes</h2>
      <ul class="cs-list">
        <li>Built the largest professional-development organization for K-12 leaders in the United States.</li>
        <li>Within two years of graduating, 70% of participants landed their first superintendency.</li>
        <li>
          Grew national cohorts from 50 to 200 and expanded a single academy into four regional
          national programs plus central-office and principal pipelines.
        </li>
        <li>
          Built and ran national leadership programming in partnership with AASA, including
          specialized pipelines for women, Latino, and urban-district leaders.
        </li>
        <li>Partnered with Apple on some of the earliest digital textbooks in education.</li>
        <li>Reached over $10M in annual revenue at peak.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="cs-step" style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">The pattern</h2>
      <p style="margin-top: 0.7rem;">
        The biggest opportunities are the gaps nobody&rsquo;s built for yet. There was no path to the
        hardest job in public education, so we built the path &mdash; then let the market pull us into
        building the rest of it. See the gap, build the standard, and let real demand tell you what
        comes next. Fix, grow, systematize, exit.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cta-band">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>Building the thing that doesn&rsquo;t exist yet?</h2>
      <a class="btn" href="/contact" title="No deck required.">Start a conversation</a>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
